<br>
Yes, it was called the Asian Financial Crisis because all countries were hit by it.  So it is no surprise that Japan got sent into a recession during this period and also had to do massive bank reforms.  Also, if the IMF had not stepped in, South Korea would have completely collapsed.  Do you get it yet?  Just because Korea was able to capitalize on a large injection of money into the economy afterwards does not change the fact that they were going to COLLAPSE COMPLETELY.<br>
<br>
You say they were going through a boom in the late 90s, but a lot of asian countries were going through a boom in the late 90s due to currency inflation and increased buying power and unsubstatiated feel good horseshit.  Classic signs of a bubble economy, which I believe isn't considered strong.<br>
<br>
So I am blowing smoke when I say that the 5 year occupation by the US in Japan following world war 2 is not the main reason Japan is such a powerful economic power?  I guess that ignores the fact that Japanese people of that generation talk of all the hardships and the amount of energy they had to spend on rebuilding the country after the US left.  Japanese men would go into work at 6am and leave for home at 11pm.  Actually they stopped by salaryman bars before they spent all of 4 hours at home...  They did this for decades but now they complain that the younger generation, reaping all the awards of the generation before them, is lazy and doesn't undstand the hardships endured.  So these millions of Japanese who worked themselves to death, I suppose they were all propped up by the US?  I mean, it must all be because of the US because they spent all of 5 years in Japan after WW2 right?  It had nothing to do with what the Japanese people wanted to do.   Actually, do you even know EXACTLY what the US did in Japan following the war?  Try to answer before you frantically search the net again if you can.<br>
<br>
I suppose you'll come back with some failed attempt at wit and insert some half baked argument.  And I'll be more than happy to tell you You are Damn Wrong all over again.<br>
<br>
Also, before someone tries to bring up the fact that the US stations troops there and Japan has no military and how they don't have to waste money on blah blah.  Well, Japan does have a military, they just call it a self defense force.  This is a common misconception.  Japan is also one of the few countries that can build their own F15s.  I guess these F15s they produce go to a nonexistant military don't they?<br>
<br>
As for Germany, I'm not terribly strong in that field, other than knowing that the German people were well renowned for efficiency and working hard.  US soldiers would remark that after an area got blown to bits, the Germans would immediately start clearing away the rubble and rebuild.  Every other country that the GIs visited never impressed them as much as that.<br>
<br>
To sum up, it is laughable for people to point to Japan as an example of how great the US did in helping it out.  Japan helped itself; only arrogant Americans try and take credit for it.  As for Germany, I suspect this statement still holds true.<br>
