I agree - corruption is bad!  In the most extreme cases, it can turn an otherwise (on paper, usually) &quot;democratic&quot; government into a dictatorship (e.g. Zimbabwe).  In less extreme cases, such as Japan and Mexico, it can result in a single party controlling a country for decades.<br>
<br>
The problem is (and here we get into nasty tangled comparitive politics debates) in all except the most extreme cases, there are a lot of factors to examine.  It's hard to say exactly the degree to which the corruption affects the voting outcomes, the degree to which it affects the populace (apathy, cynicism), the degree to which the corruption can be mitigated (Mexico and Japan both recently reformed or elected a non-establishment leader), etc.<br>
